{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_Kuo1HE8ExrOv8h48P09Y215n","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tid: plan_tables\n3\toutput:\n4\t  tables: array\n5\tdependsOn: [plan_app, read_sources, user_stories]\n6\trole: general\n7\tfunctions: []\n8\t---\n9\t\n10\tDetail EVERY table `plan_app` planned into a source-grounded data model — one entry per\n11\t`plan_app.tables`, same set, no additions and no drops (membership was decided upstream where the whole\n12\tapp was in view). `query`, `read_sources` (`read_sources.summary`, the build brief), `user_stories`\n13\t(`user_stories.stories` — the jobs each table must support), and `plan_app` (`plan_app.tables`, the\n14\tBINDING list) are in scope. This is still a THINKING step — no writers.\n15\t\n16\tFor every planned table produce its full `schema` AND the actual `rows` read from the material, so the\n17\timplement step seeds data at creation. Do NOT invent rows: use only values the source states\n18\t(identifiers, contacts, dates, payments, stated totals, attribution). Mine the brief HARD for each\n19\ttable's rows before concluding it has few — the acceptance checks in `user_stories` name the specific\n20\tdata that must land. If after a genuine search a planned table truly has no rows in the material, keep\n21\tit with an empty `rows: []` and a complete schema rather than dropping it — the plan is binding — but\n22\tthat should be rare; a planned table almost always has rows if you look.\n23\t\n24\tEvery table schema needs a `title`, a `description`, and `columns` where each column has a\n25\t`description` and exactly one uuid primary key. Keys in each row object MUST match the column names.\n26\tEmit one statement:\n27\t\n28\t```typescript\n29\tcurrentTask.resolve({\n30\t  tables: [\n31\t    {\n32\t      name: '<source-derived table name>',\n33\t      schema: {\n34\t        title: '<Title>',\n35\t        description: '<what this table stores>',\n36\t        columns: {\n37\t          id: { type: 'string', description: 'Primary key', primaryKey: true, generated: 'uuid' },\n38\t          // …one column per field the record carries, each with a real description.\n39\t        },\n40\t      },\n41\t      // One object per record READ FROM THE MATERIAL. Never carry over an example value.\n42\t      rows: [ /* { id: '…', …source-derived fields } */ ],\n43\t    },\n44\t  ],\n45\t});\n46\t```\n47\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"10d74089-d65b-435d-a979-1d29f6775b52","uuid":"b76e3803-4e54-404b-897a-35376ddcbad2","timestamp":"2026-07-16T22:45:16.764Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/system-appbuilder/tasklists/build_live_project/04-plan_tables.md","content":"---\nid: plan_tables\noutput:\n  tables: array\ndependsOn: [plan_app, read_sources, user_stories]\nrole: general\nfunctions: []\n---\n\nDetail EVERY table `plan_app` planned into a source-grounded data model — one entry per\n`plan_app.tables`, same set, no additions and no drops (membership was decided upstream where the whole\napp was in view). `query`, `read_sources` (`read_sources.summary`, the build brief), `user_stories`\n(`user_stories.stories` — the jobs each table must support), and `plan_app` (`plan_app.tables`, the\nBINDING list) are in scope. This is still a THINKING step — no writers.\n\nFor every planned table produce its full `schema` AND the actual `rows` read from the material, so the\nimplement step seeds data at creation. Do NOT invent rows: use only values the source states\n(identifiers, contacts, dates, payments, stated totals, attribution). Mine the brief HARD for each\ntable's rows before concluding it has few — the acceptance checks in `user_stories` name the specific\ndata that must land. If after a genuine search a planned table truly has no rows in the material, keep\nit with an empty `rows: []` and a complete schema rather than dropping it — the plan is binding — but\nthat should be rare; a planned table almost always has rows if you look.\n\nEvery table schema needs a `title`, a `description`, and `columns` where each column has a\n`description` and exactly one uuid primary key. Keys in each row object MUST match the column names.\nEmit one statement:\n\n```typescript\ncurrentTask.resolve({\n  tables: [\n    {\n      name: '<source-derived table name>',\n      schema: {\n        title: '<Title>',\n        description: '<what this table stores>',\n        columns: {\n          id: { type: 'string', description: 'Primary key', primaryKey: true, generated: 'uuid' },\n          // …one column per field the record carries, each with a real description.\n        },\n      },\n      // One object per record READ FROM THE MATERIAL. Never carry over an example value.\n      rows: [ /* { id: '…', …source-derived fields } */ ],\n    },\n  ],\n});\n```\n","numLines":47,"startLine":1,"totalLines":47}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_VAwWRzT2qvZsn9coqGnB7oE2","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tinput:\n3\t  query: string\n4\t  attachmentIds: array\n5\t---\n6\t\n7\tBuild a complete, openable live-project app from supplied material — as a PLAN → per-item BUILD\n8\tpipeline, so no single model turn has to author a whole app at once. First read the attachments, then\n9\tdistil the request + material into the USER STORIES the app must satisfy, then make a holistic,\n10\tBINDING plan of the app (its tables, endpoints, reusable components, and MULTIPLE pages) that serves\n11\tevery story. From there each category is a `plan → implement` pair that the host fans out one file at a\n12\ttime, each planner threaded with the stories + the binding plan + the artifacts already built upstream:\n13\tplan the tables → write each table (with its source-derived rows), plan the endpoints (grounded in the\n14\treal written tables) → write each typed API, plan the components → write each reusable component, plan\n15\tthe pages → write each page (which imports the components and reads the endpoints). A final node writes\n16\tthe persistent chat layout and reports what was built. Every write is its own bounded node, so a slip on one file no longer loses the build;\n17\teach writer returns `{ ok, error? }` and validates at write time. Pages use `@app/runtime` data hooks\n18\tand `@lmthing/css` design tokens only.\n19\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"10d74089-d65b-435d-a979-1d29f6775b52","uuid":"ff44e131-1309-47d5-80f5-fdf77ec2b7ac","timestamp":"2026-07-16T22:45:16.766Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/system-appbuilder/tasklists/build_live_project/index.md","content":"---\ninput:\n  query: string\n  attachmentIds: array\n---\n\nBuild a complete, openable live-project app from supplied material — as a PLAN → per-item BUILD\npipeline, so no single model turn has to author a whole app at once. First read the attachments, then\ndistil the request + material into the USER STORIES the app must satisfy, then make a holistic,\nBINDING plan of the app (its tables, endpoints, reusable components, and MULTIPLE pages) that serves\nevery story. From there each category is a `plan → implement` pair that the host fans out one file at a\ntime, each planner threaded with the stories + the binding plan + the artifacts already built upstream:\nplan the tables → write each table (with its source-derived rows), plan the endpoints (grounded in the\nreal written tables) → write each typed API, plan the components → write each reusable component, plan\nthe pages → write each page (which imports the components and reads the endpoints). A final node writes\nthe persistent chat layout and reports what was built. Every write is its own bounded node, so a slip on one file no longer loses the build;\neach writer returns `{ ok, error? }` and validates at write time. Pages use `@app/runtime` data hooks\nand `@lmthing/css` design tokens only.\n","numLines":19,"startLine":1,"totalLines":19}}}
