{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_oamKvljQva6oY9kETK4or56J","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tid: user_stories\n3\toutput:\n4\t  stories: array\n5\t  ok: boolean\n6\tdependsOn: [read_sources]\n7\trole: general\n8\tfunctions: []\n9\t---\n10\t\n11\tTurn the user's request and the supplied material into the concrete USER STORIES the app must satisfy —\n12\tthe backbone every downstream plan is measured against. `query` (the user's own words) and\n13\t`read_sources` (`read_sources.summary`, the source-derived build brief) are in scope. This is a THINKING\n14\tstep — no writers. Aggregate BOTH: what the user asked for AND what the material proves they have, then\n15\tname the things the user will actually DO with the app once it is open.\n16\t\n17\tWrite one story per distinct job-to-be-done, GROUNDED in the material (never invent a job the sources\n18\tand request don't support). Cover every kind of record the material carries — if the source has costs,\n19\tthere is a \"review the costs\" story; if it has dated legs, an \"see the itinerary in order\" story; if it\n20\thas contacts/fees/rules, stories that surface them. Each story has a stable `id`, the actor (`as`), what\n21\tthey `want`, the payoff (`soThat`), and 1–3 concrete `acceptance` checks phrased against real data the\n22\tsources contain. These stories drive `plan_app` (which turns them into an app shape) and every planner\n23\tbelow (which each honor them). Emit exactly one statement:\n24\t\n25\t```typescript\n26\tcurrentTask.resolve({\n27\t  stories: [\n28\t    {\n29\t      id: '<kebab-story-id>',\n30\t      as: '<the person using the app, e.g. the traveller>',\n31\t      want: '<what they want to do>',\n32\t      soThat: '<the payoff>',\n33\t      // 1–3 checks a finished app must pass, each naming real supplied data:\n34\t      acceptance: [ '<concrete, source-grounded criterion>' ],\n35\t    },\n36\t  ],\n37\t  ok: true,\n38\t});\n39\t```\n40\t"}]},"parent_t